    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. i'm kinda confused. whats escrow actually and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral, third-party vault where the money for your new home sits safely until the very last moment, ensuring neither the seller nor the buyer can touch it prematurely. It's a crucial safety net, especially in a busy market like Toronto, because it prevents the seller from walking away with the deposit before the deed is signed and the buyer from paying the full price before taking possession. Without it, you'd be at the mercy of a single party, which is a recipe for a very expensive and stressful situation.\n\nThink of it like a game of musical chairs where the music stops only when everyone is seated; the escrow agent is the conductor who ensures the rules are followed before the final \"cut\" happens. In Toronto specifically, the complexity of the land transfer tax and the strict timelines mean this middleman is your best friend. If you skip this step, you might find yourself in a legal tangle that could cost you thousands in legal fees, not to mention the potential for a deal to fall through entirely.\n\nThe process is straightforward: the realtor opens the account, you wire the funds, and the agent holds them until the lawyer or title company clears all the title issues and the closing documents are ready",
      "source": "target",
