    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so it's basically just a middleman holding the cash so nobody gets ripped off. but who actually manages the account? is it the realtor or a lawyer or something? and how do i know the money is actually safe while it's just sitting there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The management of that account is a bit like a high-stakes game of tag, but with much more paperwork and a lot fewer chances of getting caught in the rain. In Ontario, it's usually a licensed lawyer or a title company who acts as the \"escrow agent,\" though sometimes the realtor's office handles the administrative side while the lawyer holds the actual funds. You can think of the realtor as the one who hands you the map, but the lawyer is the one who actually guards the treasure chest.\n\nTo ensure the money is safe, it's not just sitting in a generic bank account; it's held in a segregated trust account. This is like putting your cash in a special, locked box that the bank keeps strictly separate from their own operating funds. If the bank goes bust, your money is still yours because it's not mixed with their other assets. It's a legal requirement, and if the bank tried to touch it, the court would immediately send a goblin to the bank manager to make sure they didn't break the rules.\n\nYou can verify this safety by asking your lawyer or the escrow agent for the \"trust account confirmation\" right after the account is opened. They will give you a letter stating",
      "source": "target",
